{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651767"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:28:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:28:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18494"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18494"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.14,0.36,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11223"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11223"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18494"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6637"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe coronary arteries arise from the aortic sinuses and provide the primary blood supply to the heart muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal branching pattern of the coronary arteries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left main continues as circumflex with diagonal branches","Right coronary divides into anterior descending and circumflex arteries","Right coronary divides into posterior descending and marginal arteries","Left main continues as anterior descending with circumflex branch","Left main divides into anterior descending and circumflex arteries"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft main coronary artery divides into the left anterior descending and circumflex arteries (image)\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the normal anatomical branching pattern seen in most people. The left anterior descending artery runs in the anterior interventricular groove, while the circumflex artery courses in the left atrioventricular groove.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft main continues as circumflex with diagonal branches\u003C/strong\u003E - The left anterior descending artery is a major branch of the left main coronary artery\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight coronary divides into anterior descending and circumflex arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The right coronary artery typically gives rise to the posterior descending artery in right-dominant circulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight coronary divides into posterior descending and marginal arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - This is correct however, is not the main branching pattern being asked about\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft main continues as anterior descending with circumflex branch\u003C/strong\u003E - This implies an incorrect hierarchy where the circumflex is subordinate to the anterior descending\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the normal coronary anatomy is essential for interpreting cardiac imaging and managing coronary artery disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The left main coronary artery divides into the left anterior descending and circumflex arteries.","The right coronary artery typically supplies the right ventricle and posterior third of the interventricular septum.","The left anterior descending artery supplies the anterior two-thirds of the interventricular septum and anterior left ventricle."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cCoronary Arteries\u201d by Patrick J. Lynch\u00a0is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported license. (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Coronary_arteries.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18494"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21414"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21414","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21414"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dfTdnsn2GFm2mxAtnebxaShyrPX9a7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/dfTdnsn2GFm2mxAtnebxaShyrPX9a7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":412}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T11:42:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T17:56:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11223"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms"